Here is the solution to the problem:

```julia
function timezone_bumper(dt::DateTime, bump::Int = 3)
    if !(eltype(dt) <: DateTime)
        throw(ArgumentError("Input must be of type DateTime"))
    end
    return DateTime(dt.year, dt.month, dt.day, dt.hour + bump, dt.minute, dt.second)
end
```

This function takes a DateTime object `dt` and an optional integer `bump` (defaulting to 3). It checks if the input is of type DateTime. If not, it throws an error. If the input is of type DateTime, it creates a new DateTime object with the same year, month, and day as the input, but with the hour incremented by `bump`.
